INSERT INTO questions (subject, topic, difficulty, question_text, choices, correct_answer, explanation, exam_type) VALUES
('General Education','English','medium','Who is the author of the Philippine national novel "Noli Me Tangere"?','[{"key":"A","text":"Francisco Balagtas"},{"key":"B","text":"José Rizal"},{"key":"C","text":"Nick Joaquin"},{"key":"D","text":"F. Sionil José"}]','B','Noli Me Tangere (Touch Me Not) was written by José Rizal and published in 1887 in Berlin, Germany.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The main character in Noli Me Tangere is:','[{"key":"A","text":"Simoun"},{"key":"B","text":"Padre Damaso"},{"key":"C","text":"Crisostomo Ibarra"},{"key":"D","text":"Elias"}]','C','Juan Crisostomo Ibarra y Magsalin is the protagonist of Noli Me Tangere, representing the educated Filipino youth.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','In El Filibusterismo, Ibarra returns under the alias:','[{"key":"A","text":"Basilio"},{"key":"B","text":"Simoun"},{"key":"C","text":"Isagani"},{"key":"D","text":"Placido"}]','B','In El Filibusterismo (1891), Crisostomo Ibarra returns as the wealthy jeweler Simoun, now plotting revolution against the Spanish colonial government.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','Florante at Laura is a masterpiece written by:','[{"key":"A","text":"Francisco Balagtas"},{"key":"B","text":"Lope K. Santos"},{"key":"C","text":"José Corazon de Jesus"},{"key":"D","text":"Amado V. Hernandez"}]','A','Florante at Laura (1838) is a famous awit (lyrical poem) written by Francisco Baltazar (Balagtas), considered the prince of Tagalog poets.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','The folk epic "Biag ni Lam-ang" originated from which ethnic group?','[{"key":"A","text":"Visayan"},{"key":"B","text":"Ilocano"},{"key":"C","text":"Tagalog"},{"key":"D","text":"Maranao"}]','B','Biag ni Lam-ang (Life of Lam-ang) is the Ilocano folk epic, considered the first recorded Philippine folk epic. Lam-ang is the hero with supernatural powers.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','Nick Joaquin is known by the pen name:','[{"key":"A","text":"Quijano de Manila"},{"key":"B","text":"Amado V. Hernandez"},{"key":"C","text":"Jose Garcia Villa"},{"key":"D","text":"Carlos P. Romulo"}]','A','Nick Joaquin, considered one of the greatest Filipino writers in English, used the pen name "Quijano de Manila" for his essays and journalism.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','The Maranao epic "Darangen" features which hero?','[{"key":"A","text":"Lam-ang"},{"key":"B","text":"Tuwaang"},{"key":"C","text":"Bantugan"},{"key":"D","text":"Agyu"}]','C','The Darangen is the Maranao epic cycle featuring Prince Bantugan as the hero. It is recognized by UNESCO as an intangible cultural heritage.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The poem "Ako ay Filipino" was written by:','[{"key":"A","text":"Jose Rizal"},{"key":"B","text":"Carlos P. Romulo"},{"key":"C","text":"Manuel L. Quezon"},{"key":"D","text":"Claro M. Recto"}]','B','Carlos P. Romulo wrote "I Am a Filipino" (Ako ay Filipino), a famous essay expressing Filipino nationalism. He was also the first Asian to win a Pulitzer Prize.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','The Philippine literary genre "corrido" is a:','[{"key":"A","text":"Short story set in rural areas"},{"key":"B","text":"Narrative poem sung or chanted, usually about a Christian hero"},{"key":"C","text":"One-act play about everyday life"},{"key":"D","text":"Satirical essay criticizing the Spanish government"}]','B','A corrido is a narrative verse form, often in octosyllabic lines, featuring a Christian hero performing heroic deeds. It developed during the Spanish period.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','F. Sionil José''s Rosales Saga deals mainly with:','[{"key":"A","text":"Philippine mythology and pre-colonial life"},{"key":"B","text":"Filipino struggle against colonialism, poverty, and social injustice"},{"key":"C","text":"The life of Filipino expatriates in America"},{"key":"D","text":"Comedy of manners in Manila''s elite society"}]','B','Francisco Sionil José''s Rosales Saga (5 novels) chronicles Filipino society''s struggle against Spanish and American colonialism, poverty, and the quest for justice.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','Which Philippine folk tale explains how the sun and moon came to be in the sky?','[{"key":"A","text":"The Story of Bathala"},{"key":"B","text":"Why the Sky is High"},{"key":"C","text":"The Sun and the Moon"},{"key":"D","text":"Malakas at Maganda"}]','D','Malakas at Maganda (Strong One and Beautiful One) is the Tagalog creation myth explaining the origin of the first man and woman, and other versions explain the sun and moon.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The Tagalog folk epic that tells of a hero born with supernatural powers from bamboo is:','[{"key":"A","text":"Hudhud"},{"key":"B","text":"Biag ni Lam-ang"},{"key":"C","text":"Hinilawod"},{"key":"D","text":"Tuwaang"}]','B','Lam-ang (Biag ni Lam-ang) is born speaking, walks at birth, and has fantastic supernatural abilities in this Ilocano epic.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','The "Hudhud" epic is from which Philippine ethnic group?','[{"key":"A","text":"Ilongot"},{"key":"B","text":"Ifugao"},{"key":"C","text":"Kalinga"},{"key":"D","text":"T''boli"}]','B','The Hudhud chants are a form of Ifugao oral literature, recognized by UNESCO as a Masterpiece of Oral and Intangible Heritage. They are sung during rice harvests.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','Lualhati Bautista''s "Dekada ''70" depicts:','[{"key":"A","text":"Life during the Japanese occupation"},{"key":"B","text":"A Filipino family''s experience under Marcos''s Martial Law"},{"key":"C","text":"Pre-colonial Philippine society"},{"key":"D","text":"Filipino workers abroad in the 1970s"}]','B','Dekada ''70 (1983) by Lualhati Bautista is a novel set during the Marcos era, following the Bartolome family as they cope with the social and political turmoil of Martial Law.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','The poem "Banaag at Sikat" by Lope K. Santos represents:','[{"key":"A","text":"A romantic love story"},{"key":"B","text":"Social realism and the struggle of the Filipino working class"},{"key":"C","text":"Philippine mythology"},{"key":"D","text":"Religious devotion during Spanish times"}]','B','Banaag at Sikat (Glimmer and Sunrise, 1906) by Lope K. Santos is considered the first socialist novel in Philippine literature, depicting the lives of laborers.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','Nick Joaquin''s play "Portrait of the Artist as Filipino" deals with:','[{"key":"A","text":"José Rizal''s execution"},{"key":"B","text":"The conflict between old Filipino values and modernization"},{"key":"C","text":"The EDSA Revolution"},{"key":"D","text":"A Filipino artist''s life in New York"}]','B','The play depicts two sisters who must decide whether to sell their father''s (a forgotten painter) masterpiece, symbolizing the tension between tradition and modernity.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The baybayin word "Ka" consists of:','[{"key":"A","text":"One character"},{"key":"B","text":"Two characters"},{"key":"C","text":"Three characters"},{"key":"D","text":"It cannot be written in baybayin"}]','A','In Baybayin, each character represents a consonant-vowel syllable. "Ka" is a single character (the ka syllable).','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','The "Pasyon" is a Philippine literary form that:','[{"key":"A","text":"Recounts the life and passion of Jesus Christ"},{"key":"B","text":"Tells pre-colonial creation myths"},{"key":"C","text":"Satirizes Spanish friars"},{"key":"D","text":"Narrates heroic battles of Philippine warriors"}]','A','The Pasyon (Pasyong Mahal) is a verse narrative of the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus, chanted during Holy Week. It blended Christian teaching with Filipino culture.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','Carlos Bulosan''s "America is in the Heart" is classified as:','[{"key":"A","text":"A collection of Philippine folk tales"},{"key":"B","text":"An autobiographical novel about Filipino immigrant workers in America"},{"key":"C","text":"A historical novel set during WWII"},{"key":"D","text":"A comedy about Filipino society"}]','B','America is in the Heart (1946) is Carlos Bulosan''s semi-autobiographical account of his experiences as a Filipino immigrant worker facing poverty and racial discrimination in the USA.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The tagasining (poet) Francisco Balagtas wrote most of his works in:','[{"key":"A","text":"English"},{"key":"B","text":"Spanish"},{"key":"C","text":"Tagalog"},{"key":"D","text":"Ilocano"}]','C','Francisco Baltazar (Balagtas) composed his works primarily in Tagalog, earning him the title "Prince of Tagalog Poets."','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','The novel "Noli Me Tangere" was written in which language?','[{"key":"A","text":"Tagalog"},{"key":"B","text":"Latin"},{"key":"C","text":"Spanish"},{"key":"D","text":"English"}]','C','Rizal wrote Noli Me Tangere in Spanish, the language of the educated class and colonial administration at the time. The title is Latin for "Touch Me Not."','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','Who is considered the Father of Philippine Literature in English?','[{"key":"A","text":"Nick Joaquin"},{"key":"B","text":"Jose Garcia Villa"},{"key":"C","text":"Carlos P. Romulo"},{"key":"D","text":"Manuel E. Arguilla"}]','B','Jose Garcia Villa is considered the "Father of Philippine Literature in English" and the most celebrated Filipino poet in English, known for his experimental "comma poems."','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The "kundiman" is a Filipino:','[{"key":"A","text":"Traditional war dance"},{"key":"B","text":"Love song with patriotic undertones"},{"key":"C","text":"Morality play performed during fiestas"},{"key":"D","text":"Epic poem about heroes"}]','B','Kundiman is a genre of Filipino love song characterized by a slow, sentimental melody. During the Propaganda and Revolution era, many kundimans had hidden patriotic meanings.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','In the sarsuwela (sarswela), which best describes this theatrical form?','[{"key":"A","text":"A Filipino ballet with pre-colonial themes"},{"key":"B","text":"A musical play in Filipino with singing, dialogue, and dance"},{"key":"C","text":"A religious morality play adapted from Spanish"},{"key":"D","text":"A one-act comedy set in urban Manila"}]','B','Sarsuwela is a Filipino form of musical theater with spoken dialogue, songs, and dances. It flourished in the late 19th and early 20th centuries as a vehicle for social commentary.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','Amado V. Hernandez''s novel "Mga Ibong Mandaragit" (Rapacious Birds) criticized:','[{"key":"A","text":"Spanish friars'' abuse of power"},{"key":"B","text":"Corruption and exploitation of the poor by the Philippine elite and politicians"},{"key":"C","text":"American cultural imperialism"},{"key":"D","text":"Japanese brutality during WWII"}]','B','Hernandez''s novel (1969) exposes corruption in Philippine society and politics, depicting the exploitation of workers and the poor by the powerful ruling class.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The literary device where a story within a story is told is called:','[{"key":"A","text":"Allegory"},{"key":"B","text":"Frame narrative"},{"key":"C","text":"Stream of consciousness"},{"key":"D","text":"Satire"}]','B','A frame narrative (frame story) is a literary technique where one story serves as the container for another story told within it.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','Jose Garcia Villa''s "comma poems" are notable for:','[{"key":"A","text":"Using traditional Filipino verse forms"},{"key":"B","text":"Placing commas between every word for rhythmic effect"},{"key":"C","text":"Rhyming every other line"},{"key":"D","text":"Alternating English and Tagalog"}]','B','Villa inserted commas between every word in some poems, creating a deliberate, meditative rhythm. Critics debate whether this was experimental genius or an affectation.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','Which of the following is a characteristic of the awit (lyrical poem)?','[{"key":"A","text":"8-syllable lines (octosyllabic)"},{"key":"B","text":"12-syllable lines (dodecasyllabic)"},{"key":"C","text":"Free verse with no set meter"},{"key":"D","text":"14-line sonnet form"}]','B','Awit is written in 12-syllable (dodecasyllabic) lines arranged in quatrains (4-line stanzas). Corrido uses 8-syllable (octosyllabic) lines.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','Manuel E. Arguilla''s short story "How My Brother Leon Brought Home a Wife" is notable for:','[{"key":"A","text":"Its dark portrayal of urban Manila''s poverty"},{"key":"B","text":"Its vivid depiction of Ilocano rural life and values"},{"key":"C","text":"A critique of Spanish colonialism"},{"key":"D","text":"Its experimental use of stream of consciousness"}]','B','Arguilla''s story beautifully depicts the Ilocano countryside and family life as Leon introduces his city-bred wife Maria to his rural family home.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','The "Hinilawod" epic originates from which region and ethnic group?','[{"key":"A","text":"Bicol region, Bicolano people"},{"key":"B","text":"Western Visayas, Sulod-Bukidnon people"},{"key":"C","text":"Mindanao, Maranao people"},{"key":"D","text":"Cordillera, Ifugao people"}]','B','The Hinilawod (Adventures of Humadapnon) is an epic from Panay, recited by the Sulod-Bukidnon people of Western Visayas, one of the longest epics in the world.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The literary term for the central message or main idea of a literary work is:','[{"key":"A","text":"Plot"},{"key":"B","text":"Setting"},{"key":"C","text":"Theme"},{"key":"D","text":"Tone"}]','C','The theme is the central idea or universal message that the author conveys through the story, beyond just the plot events.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','Bienvenido Santos is known for his stories about:','[{"key":"A","text":"Philippine rural folk and their traditions"},{"key":"B","text":"Filipino immigrants in America experiencing loneliness and displacement"},{"key":"C","text":"Heroes of the Philippine Revolution"},{"key":"D","text":"City life during the Marcos era"}]','B','Santos''s major works (e.g., Scent of Apples, You Lovely People) focus on the loneliness and displacement of Filipino exiles and immigrants in the United States.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','The term "komiks" in Philippine literature refers to:','[{"key":"A","text":"Comedy plays performed in fiestas"},{"key":"B","text":"Philippine comic books that popularized Filipino literature and vernacular language"},{"key":"C","text":"A satirical newspaper column"},{"key":"D","text":"Humorous folk tales"}]','B','Komiks are Philippine-style comic books that became immensely popular from the 1950s to 1990s. They serialized stories and popularized Filipino writers like Rizal Reyes.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','The epic "Agyu" or "Olahing" belongs to which Mindanao ethnic group?','[{"key":"A","text":"Maranao"},{"key":"B","text":"Maguindanao"},{"key":"C","text":"Manobo (Bukidnon)"},{"key":"D","text":"Bagobo"}]','C','The Olahing (also called Agyu) is the epic of the Manobo people of Bukidnon, Mindanao, featuring Agyu (Olahing) as the heroic leader guiding his people to the land of the gods.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','A "tanaga" is a Filipino short poem with:','[{"key":"A","text":"7-7-7-7 syllable lines with end rhyme"},{"key":"B","text":"5-7-5 syllable pattern (haiku-like)"},{"key":"C","text":"14 lines in iambic pentameter"},{"key":"D","text":"Free verse with no set syllable count"}]','A','The tanaga is a traditional Filipino short poem with 4 lines of 7 syllables each, following an AABB, ABAB, or AAAA rhyme scheme.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','Rizal''s "Mi Ultimo Adios" (My Last Farewell) is a poem written:','[{"key":"A","text":"In Tagalog, two months before his execution"},{"key":"B","text":"In Spanish on the night before his execution"},{"key":"C","text":"In English, published in a European newspaper"},{"key":"D","text":"In Spanish, written during his exile in Dapitan"}]','B','Rizal wrote "Mi Ultimo Adios" in Spanish on the eve of his execution (December 29, 1896). He hid it inside an alcohol lamp and gave it to his family.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','Which of the following best describes the literary movement known as "Social Realism" in Philippine literature?','[{"key":"A","text":"Literature that romanticizes pre-colonial Filipino life"},{"key":"B","text":"Literature that reflects the harsh realities of poverty, oppression, and class struggle"},{"key":"C","text":"Literature that celebrates American democratic values"},{"key":"D","text":"Literature that focuses on individual psychological development"}]','B','Social Realism in Philippine literature depicts the social conditions of the marginalized — poverty, labor exploitation, colonial oppression — with writers like Amado V. Hernandez championing this form.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The "balagtasan" is a Filipino:','[{"key":"A","text":"Dance performed during harvest festivals"},{"key":"B","text":"Poetic debate or tournament in verse"},{"key":"C","text":"Religious procession during Holy Week"},{"key":"D","text":"Traditional wedding ceremony"}]','B','A balagtasan is a poetic joust or debate in verse, named after Francisco Balagtas. Two poets argue opposing sides of a topic through improvised or prepared verses.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','What is the primary theme of José Rizal''s novels Noli Me Tangere and El Filibusterismo?','[{"key":"A","text":"The importance of Catholic faith to Filipino identity"},{"key":"B","text":"The abuses of Spanish colonialism and the awakening of Filipino national consciousness"},{"key":"C","text":"The romantic struggles of Filipino ilustrados"},{"key":"D","text":"The natural beauty of the Philippine archipelago"}]','B','Rizal''s novels expose the corruption, oppression, and abuses of Spanish rule and the Catholic friars, awakening Filipinos to the need for reform and eventual independence.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','In literary criticism, "postcolonial literature" in the Philippines refers to:','[{"key":"A","text":"Literature written during the Spanish colonial period"},{"key":"B","text":"Literature that examines the effects and legacy of colonial rule on Filipino identity and culture"},{"key":"C","text":"Literature promoting American democratic values"},{"key":"D","text":"Literature about Filipinos living after independence in 1946"}]','B','Postcolonial literature analyzes how colonial experiences shaped Filipino culture, language, and identity, often critiquing persistent colonial attitudes in a formally independent nation.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The "duplo" is a pre-colonial Filipino literary form that is a:','[{"key":"A","text":"Heroic epic chanted during rituals"},{"key":"B","text":"Short religious prayer"},{"key":"C","text":"Debate in verse between men and women"},{"key":"D","text":"Funeral song"}]','C','The duplo is a traditional verbal joust in which men and women engage in witty poetic repartee. It was later adapted with Christian themes during the Spanish period.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','Which of the following Philippine short stories is considered a classic of Filipino literature in English?','[{"key":"A","text":"Florante at Laura by Balagtas"},{"key":"B","text":"Dead Stars by Paz Marquez Benitez"},{"key":"C","text":"Noli Me Tangere by Rizal"},{"key":"D","text":"Biag ni Lam-ang (anonymous)"}]','B','"Dead Stars" (1925) by Paz Marquez Benitez is considered the first important short story written in English by a Filipino, a landmark in Philippine literature in English.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','The poem "To the Filipino Youth" (A La Juventud Filipina) was written by Rizal when he was:','[{"key":"A","text":"31 years old, while in Dapitan"},{"key":"B","text":"18 years old, winning a literary contest in Manila"},{"key":"C","text":"25 years old, while studying in Spain"},{"key":"D","text":"21 years old, while writing Noli"}]','B','Rizal wrote "A La Juventud Filipina" in 1879 at age 18, winning the highest prize at a literary contest sponsored by the Liceo Artistico-Literario de Manila.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','The setting of Noli Me Tangere is primarily:','[{"key":"A","text":"Pre-colonial Philippines"},{"key":"B","text":"Colonial Philippines during the late 19th century"},{"key":"C","text":"Philippines during American colonial rule"},{"key":"D","text":"Contemporary Philippines"}]','B','Noli Me Tangere is set in 19th-century colonial Philippines, depicting life under Spanish rule with themes of corruption, injustice, and emerging nationalism.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','"Ang Ibong Adarna" is a corrido (narrative poem) featuring a magical bird. It was published in:','[{"key":"A","text":"The pre-colonial period"},{"key":"B","text":"The Spanish colonial period"},{"key":"C","text":"The American colonial period"},{"key":"D","text":"The Commonwealth period"}]','B','Ibong Adarna was published during the Spanish colonial period. The exact authorship is disputed, but it is attributed to José de la Cruz (Huseng Sisiw) or an anonymous author.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','hard','The anting-anting in Philippine folklore is a:','[{"key":"A","text":"Traditional dance associated with harvest rituals"},{"key":"B","text":"Magical amulet believed to give supernatural power or protection"},{"key":"C","text":"Type of healing ritual performed by a babaylan"},{"key":"D","text":"Traditional Filipino weapon"}]','B','Anting-anting are amulets or talismans in Philippine folk tradition, believed to confer supernatural powers, invulnerability, or special abilities on the bearer.','secondary'),
('General Education','English','easy','Which of the following is a recognized epic from the Bicol region?','[{"key":"A","text":"Darangen"},{"key":"B","text":"Ibalon"},{"key":"C","text":"Hinilawod"},{"key":"D","text":"Hudhud"}]','B','The Ibalon is the Bicolano epic narrating the adventures of three heroes — Baltog, Handyong, and Bantong — in the ancient land of Ibalon (Bicol).','secondary'),
('General Education','English','medium','In Philippine literature, the "pasyon" tradition is associated with which religious practice?','[{"key":"A","text":"Christmas novena masses (Simbang Gabi)"},{"key":"B","text":"Holy Week observances, particularly the chanting of Christ''s passion"},{"key":"C","text":"The feast of All Saints'' Day (Undas)"},{"key":"D","text":"The June feast of St. John the Baptist"}]','B','The Pasyon is chanted during Holy Week (Mahal na Araw), particularly during Good Friday vigils. Communities gather to chant the passion narrative through the night.','secondary');
